IWI US TAVOR® SAR OVERVIEW
 
The dynamics of the battlefield are forever changing. With the increasing threat of terrorism in our streets to the evolving situations of combat applications, a new paradigm in firearms was required. In 1982, with the foresight of what the modern battlefield was becoming, IWI in a decade long collaboration with the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) Research & Development teams, developed the new standard issue weapon for the IDF. The TAVOR® was born. Mr. Zalman Shebs, known as the “father of the TAVOR,” spearheaded the team to develop a weapon system that was capable of moving from open field conflicts to close-quarter engagements and from daylight to nighttime capabilities – seamlessly on a single mission. In the late 1990’s through the early 2000’s, the TAVOR underwent unprecedented testing unlike any weapons system anywhere. The TAVOR began trials with IDF units testing for ergonomics. The TAVOR then entered the IDF NCO Infantry School for extensive field tests and finally, in 2002, the TAVOR was given to an army company in the Givati Brigade for real-world testing and use. By September, 2003, the IDF had chosen the TAVOR rifle as the standard issue for their infantry troops. Today the TAVOR rifles are in service with IDF Infantry troops and the IDF Special Forces in Israel along with many military and law enforcement agencies in the world.
 
IWI and IWI US have brought the same dedication to craft and commitment to performance and reliability to the American customer with the TAVOR SAR rifle.

-Bullpup configuration allows for short rifle convenience with long rifle accuracy
-Optimized ergonomic design for increased comfort and ease-of-use
-Clean, long stroke piston operation
-Detachable, cold hammer-forged barrel (CHF), chrome-lined with 1:10 twist, CrMoV steel
-100% ambidextrous configuration and operation. No additional parts required to convert 9mm Parabellum to LH configuration
-Integral ambidextrous front and rear quick detachable sling swivel receptacles with push button swivels
-Simple field stripping into easily serviceable subassemblies
-Mil-Std 100% interchangeability of all TAVOR SAR parts
-Last round - bolt holds open on an empty magazine

Absolutely MINT condition, featured HH pickup configuration and a locking Floyd Rose Trem System, 24 frets, rosewood fretboard on a Neck through maple neck, reverse headstock, and 3 way selector, in the gorgeous Atlantic Blue Metallic (569) Finish
The reverse headstocks on the Stagemasters allow for completely straight string pull. Another nice feature is the inclusion of a brass bridge sustain block on the licensed Floyd Rose bridge and rear-mounted electronics allowing for a guitar with no pickguard.

Action is great, sound is also amazing, a beautiful guitar all around.
Comes with a Hard Case, and a Peavey Rage 158 TransTube Amp and a fresh new set of #9 Strings

Specs:

Fender Stagemaster V4:
A reverse headstock
A Licensed Floyd Rose Locking Tremolo System w/ brass bridge sustain block
2x Humbucker Pickups
A contoured neck heel (Rounded corner where the neck meets the body)
3 piece Maple Neck Through Body w/ Rosewood Fretboard
A slightly narrower body than earlier models
24 fret necks (Early models had 22 fret necks)
One volume and one tone control
Knife selector switch (3-way or 5-way)

Peavey Rage 158 Transtube Amp:
15 Watts RMS into 4 Ohms
Pre and Post Gain Channel
Transtube technolgy
1/4 Headphone port

Well to start things off this is a well built and well maintained all in one package. It is down right turn key there is not much if anything you can add to it accept for optics. postcontent:
Remington Model 37 Rangemaster, 22LR target rifle, Serial #095xx.  It has all matching numbers and full length stock.  It was manufactured in 1952 so it has the miracle trigger.  This gun is a shooter (setup for competition shooting) and not a safe queen; unless you want it to be (comes with an extra stock in great condition).  I am selling my complete M37 collection to fund another rifle.  So this comes with a lot of hard to find extras.  
•	Original Remington front sight w/1 insert (front sight mount included), rear sight, and receiver mount (made by Parker Hale).  I have measured this with a dial indicator and the elevation and windage is spot on.  It also comes with original aperture with “6” predetermined size holes.
•	Single shot adapter.
•	Extra Remington Model 37 stock (full length).  It is great condition, no dings or scratches.  Includes front sling swivel hardware.
•	Original Redfield receiver mount.  This is a very hard to find mount.  
•	Original Unertl scope mounting blocks.
•	Handstop
•	Trigger Shoe (I do not know if this is original)
•	Complete spare miracle trigger.  It does have some slight damage on the mounting pin holes on one side.  A gunsmith could easily fix this or can be used for spare parts. 
•	Spare front guard bow screw nut
•	Original leather sling.
•	Quick detach sling hook.
•	Original front sling swivel
•	Original manual.
Now for the nitty gritty details.  The barrel bluing is on the lighter side, but there are zero rust spots.  When I bought the gun, it arrived with a crack at the wrist of the gun.  I had my gunsmith fix the crack with threaded rod and epoxy.  You can hardly tell where the crack was and it is completely solid.  I leave the barreled action in the original stock 95% of the time so I don’t mess up the extra stock I bought.  When I got it, it also had plumbers putty in the barrel channel (1/3 of the length of the barrel).  The putty was deteriorating, so my gunsmith sanded it out.  Luckily he didn’t sand away the stamping numbers in the barrel channel.  
This rifle has a great back story too and is probably one of kind.  It was originally export to Great Britain so it has all the British stamps on it.  Then it was imported back to the United States (came back home!).  This is a great rifle and fun to shoot. Only reason I am selling it is because I don’t shoot it enough and need funds for another project.  I am looking for a good home for this rifle.
